# Build context = aviation_feeder/. The Dockerfile copies exactly three things
# out of it: aviation_feeder_mqtt/, rootfs/, and patch-mlat-client.py. Everything
# else is add-on metadata that Home Assistant reads straight from the repo, or
# developer files. Excluding them keeps the context small -- and, more
# importantly, keeps the image reproducible.

# --- Correctness, not just tidiness ---------------------------------------
# `COPY aviation_feeder_mqtt /opt/aviation_feeder_mqtt` takes the WHOLE directory,
# so a stray local __pycache__ gets baked into the image -- including bytecode
# from whatever Python the developer happens to run. We were shipping
# cpython-314 .pyc into an image whose python3 is 3.13. That makes image contents
# depend on the builder's machine, and every local test run regenerates the .pyc,
# changing the COPY layer's hash and busting its build cache (and every layer
# after it). The Dockerfile runs `python3 -m compileall` anyway, so the correct
# in-image bytecode is generated at build time.
# NB: the `**/` prefixes are load-bearing. Docker matches .dockerignore patterns
# with Go's filepath.Match against the path relative to the context root, so a
# bare `__pycache__/` matches ONLY a top-level one -- it would NOT match the
# nested aviation_feeder_mqtt/__pycache__/, which is the one that actually gets
# copied into the image.
**/__pycache__/
**/*.py[cod]
**/.pytest_cache/
**/.mypy_cache/
**/.venv/

# --- Add-on metadata: HA reads these from the repo, never COPY'd into the image
config.json
translations/
icon.png
brand/

# --- Developer docs: not part of the image --------------------------------
*.md

# --- Build plumbing itself -------------------------------------------------
Dockerfile
.dockerignore
